  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Enfeoffment of Liu Clan, Wife of Xu Jing, as Lady of Pengcheng
  author: Choe Chiwon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    By official proclamation and notice herewith:

    In ancient times, when an official reached the rank of Grand Master, his wife bore the title of Court Lady, thereby gaining nobility through her husband and becoming honored in the world. How much more so when she is one who, in stillness, carefully guards her words, and in action, faithfully serves her lord's endeavors—girding herself in armor, her spirit surpassing frost and snow, her accomplishments exceeding the common rabble. Should her elevation not transcend mere precedent?

    Consider Liu Clan, wife of Xu Jing, Prefect of Chu Province. Heaven-gifted in brilliance, her virtue shines forth daily. Scorning the former Wei general's misadventure in Luoyang, she has long admired our enlightened court. When recently the throne commanded her husband to suppress the rebels, she resolved to share his burden—her heart ablaze with loyalty. With her own hands she marshaled the trained soldiers, leading distant assaults upon the garrison walls. Casting off the silk robes of her station, she braved the dust and tumult of battle long and perilously. Her four virtues overflow; she has proven herself in the six strategies. This is no mere honor to her house—truly she is an exemplary woman of the realm.

    Since her husband has ascended to high office, should not his wife likewise be adorned with corresponding rank? We cannot exalt the pine tree's noble shadow to pierce the clouds while leaving the clinging vine to languish in humble earth. Therefore, acting upon this merit, we issue this decree:

    Liu Clan is hereby enfeoffed as Lady of Pengcheng. Let this proclamation be recorded and reported to the throne, and let all concerned be notified thereof.
  footnotes:
    - The 'four virtues' (四德) traditionally refer to obedience, purity, compassion, and industriousness expected of women in Confucian society.
    - The 'six strategies' (六韜) are the military doctrines attributed to Lü Wang, suggesting the lady demonstrated strategic wisdom in military affairs.
    - Pengcheng was an ancient territory and honorific title, making this enfeoffment a substantial elevation in rank.
